    <div class="documentTop">        
        
        <h1>Department for Climate Change and Pollution Control</h1>
        
        <div class="pageDescription"><p>The department consists of three sections and an administrative unit. The department’s responsibilities includes development of environmental policies and strategies in the areas of climate and energy, including the Governments International Climate and Forest Initiative. It furthers covers hazardous chemicals, wastes, local air pollution and noise, and environmental data and monitoring. The department is responsible for the Norwegian Pollution Control Authority, and for the Norwegian Maritime Directorate on environmental related issues. To a large degree the department’s work is related to development of legal, administrative and economic instruments. Further, on the development and implementation of international legal instruments, particularly within the EEA, The department is responsible for a number of international environmental agreements, including the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change and the Kyoto Protocol, the UNECE Convention on Long-range Transboundary Air Pollution, UN International Maritime Organisation (IMO) conventions, and chemical conventions like the Basel Convention, the Stockholm Convention and the Rotterdam Convention.</p></div>        
